When should you use Spring 5.x?
Use Spring 5.3.x only as an intermediate migration step if:
You want to keep javax.* temporarily.
You are still deploying to Tomcat 9.
You cannot migrate JAXB/JAX-WS/JPA/Validation/Servlet imports to jakarta.* yet.
You want a smaller step first:
Spring 4 → Spring 5.3 → Spring 6.2
But Spring 5.x is not the right final target for Tomcat 10.
Best path for your project
Since your webapp is later, but schema + application will move now, I suggest this path:
Plain text
Step 1:
Java 8 + Spring 4.x
        ↓
Step 2:
Java 21 compile readiness
Fix JAXB/JAX-WS external dependencies
Fix Maven plugins
Fix removed Java EE modules
        ↓
Step 3:
Move Spring 4.x → Spring 6.2.x
        ↓
Step 4:
Move all javax.* dependencies to jakarta.*
        ↓
Step 5:
Deploy application-compatible modules for Tomcat 10.1
Important warning for your application module
If your application still uses RichFaces, that is a major risk.
RichFaces is old and strongly tied to older JSF / Java EE style libraries. For Java 21 + Jakarta + Tomcat 10, RichFaces will likely create dependency conflicts. So for now:
Plain text
Schema module: migrate fully to Java 21 + Jakarta
Config module: migrate fully to Java 21 + Spring 6.2
Application module: migrate Spring services first, isolate RichFaces-related code
Webapp / JSF / RichFaces: handle separately later
Final answer
For your target architecture:
Plain text
Choose Spring Framework 6.2.x
Do not choose Spring 5.x as final target
Use Spring 5.3.x only if you need a temporary bridge while still on javax.* and Tomcat 9.
For Java 21 + Maven 3.9 + Tomcat 10.1 + Jakarta migration, Spring 6.2.x is the correct stable choice.